#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:1
msgid "`'_`, the anonymous lifetime"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.31](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.31-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust 2018 allows you to explicitly mark where a lifetime is elided, for "
"types where this elision might otherwise be unclear. To do this, you can use "
"the special lifetime `'_` much like you can explicitly mark that a type is "
"inferred with the syntax `let x: _ = ..;`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:10
msgid ""
"Let's say, for whatever reason, that we have a simple wrapper around `&'a "
"str`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:16
msgid "In Rust 2015, you might have written:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:20
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:68
msgid "// Rust 2015\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:34
msgid "In Rust 2018, you can instead write:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:38
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:85
msgid "// Rust 2018\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:52
msgid "More details"
msgstr "更多詳情"

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:54
msgid ""
"In the Rust 2015 snippet above, we've used `-> StrWrap`. However, unless you "
"take a look at the definition of `StrWrap`, it is not clear that the "
"returned value is actually borrowing something. Therefore, starting with "
"Rust 2018, it is deprecated to leave off the lifetime parameters for non-"
"reference-types (types other than `&` and `&mut`). Instead, where you "
"previously wrote `-> StrWrap`, you should now write `-> StrWrap<'_>`, making "
"clear that borrowing is occurring."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:61
msgid ""
"What exactly does `'_` mean? It depends on the context! In output contexts, "
"as in the return type of `make_wrapper`, it refers to a single lifetime for  "
"all \"output\" locations. In input contexts, a fresh lifetime is generated "
"for each \"input location\". More concretely, to understand input contexts, "
"consider the following example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:75
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:89
msgid "// some methods...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:79
msgid "We can rewrite this as:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:93
msgid ""
"This is the same, because for each `'_`, a fresh lifetime is generated. "
"Finally, the relationship `'a: 'b` which the struct requires must be upheld."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/the-anonymous-lifetime.md:96
msgid ""
"For more details, see the [tracking issue on In-band lifetime bindings]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/44524)."
msgstr ""
